{{good article}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=[[File:Submarines Tyulen', Utka, AG-22 at Bizerte, 1922.jpg|300px]] |Ship caption=''AG-22'' (on the right) in Bizerte in 1922 }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=[[Russian Empire]] |Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Russian Empire|naval}} |Ship name=''AG-22'' |Ship ordered= |Ship awarded= |Ship builder=[[Shipyard named after 61 Communards|Russud Shipyard]], [[Mykolaiv, Ukraine|Nikolaev]] |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number= |Ship way number= |Ship laid down=1917 |Ship launched=1919 |Ship sponsor= |Ship christened= |Ship completed=1919 |Ship commissioned= |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship fate=Abandoned, November 1923, and subsequently [[ship breaking|scrapped]] |Ship status= |Ship notes= |Ship badge= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class=[[American Holland-class submarine|AG-class]] [[submarine]] |Ship displacement=*{{convert|355|LT}} surfaced *{{convert|433|LT}} submerged |Ship length={{convert|150|ft|3|in|m|1|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|16|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} |Ship draft={{convert|12|ft|6|in|m|1|abbr=on}} |Ship power=*2 × [[diesel engine]]s ({{convert|480|bhp|abbr=on|lk=in}}) *2 × [[electric motor]]s ({{convert|640|hp|abbr=on}}) |Ship propulsion=*2 × [[propeller shaft]]s *[[Diesel-electric]] |Ship speed=*{{convert|13|kn|lk=in}} (surfaced) *{{convert|10.5|kn}} (submerged) |Ship range=*{{convert|1750|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|7|kn}} (surfaced) *{{convert|25|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|3|kn}} (submerged) |Ship test depth={{convert|164|ft|m}} |Ship complement=30 |Ship armament=*4 × bow {{convert|18|in|adj=on|0}} [[torpedo tube]]s *(8 torpedoes) *1 × {{convert|47|mm|adj=on|sp=us}} gun |Ship notes= }} |} The '''Russian submarine ''AG-22''''' was an [[American Holland-class submarine|AG-class]] [[submarine]], designed by the American Holland Torpedo Boat Company/[[Electric Boat Company]], built for the [[Imperial Russian Navy]] during [[World War I]]. The submarine was fabricated in Canada, shipped to Russia and reassembled for service with the [[Black Sea Fleet]]. Her reassembly was completed in 1919 by the [[White Movement]] during the [[Russian Civil War]], and she joined [[Wrangel's fleet]] as it evacuated the [[Crimea]] in 1920 and was interned in [[Bizerte]], [[Tunisia]] in 1921. ''AG-22'' was abandoned there and subsequently [[ship breaking|scrapped]].
==Description== ''AG-22'' was a single-hulled submarine, with a pressure hull divided into five watertight compartments. The submarine had a length of {{convert|150|ft|3|in|m|1}} [[length overall|overall]], a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|16|ft|m|1}} and a [[draft (ship)|draft]] of {{convert|12|ft|6|in|m|1}}. She [[displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{convert|355|LT|t}} on the surface and {{convert|433|LT|t}} submerged. The AG-class submarines had a diving depth of {{convert|164|ft|m|1}} and a crew of 30 officers and enlisted men.<ref>Polmar & Noot, pp. 240–41</ref>
The submarine had two three-bladed propellers, each of which was driven by a {{convert|480|hp|lk=in|adj=on}} [[diesel engine]] as well as a {{convert|640|hp|0|adj=on}} [[electric motor]]s. This arrangement gave ''AG-22'' a maximum speed of {{convert|13|kn|lk=in}} while surfaced and {{convert|10.5|kn}} submerged. She had a range of {{convert|1750|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|7|kn}} while on the surface and {{convert|25|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|3|kn}} while submerged.<ref name=pn0>Polmar & Noot, p. 240</ref> Her fuel capacity was {{convert|16.5|LT|t}} of fuel oil.<ref>Watts, p. 170</ref>
The AG-class submarines were equipped with four {{convert|18|in|adj=on|0}} [[torpedo tube]]s in the bow and carried eight torpedoes. For surface combat they had one {{convert|47|mm|adj=on|sp=us}} [[deck gun]].<ref name=pn0/>
==Construction and service== The Holland 602 design was widely exported during World War I and the Imperial Russian Navy ordered a total of 17, in three batches, of a version known as the [[American Holland-class submarine|''American Holland''-class]] (AG in Russian for ''Amerikansky Golland'' (American Holland)). The submarines were to be built in Canada as [[knock-down kit]]s for assembly in Russia.<ref name=pn0/>
Steel for the first three submarines ({{ship|Russian submarine|AG-21||2}}, ''AG-22'', and {{ship|Russian submarine|AG-23||2}}) of the second batch ordered by the Russians was assembled in [[Saint John, New Brunswick]] by May 1916. Five months later, they were sent to [[Vancouver]] by rail in sections where they were loaded into ships and shipped to [[Vladivostok]]. There they were loaded onto the [[Trans-Siberian Railroad]] and transported to [[Mykolaiv, Ukraine|Nikolaev]] where they were assembled by the [[Shipyard named after 61 Communards|Russud Shipyard]]. Assembly was delayed by the unrest caused by the [[Russian Revolution]] and the subsequent Russian Civil War and was not completed until 1919. By this time, Nikolaev was controlled by the Whites and they took ''AG-22'' with them when they evacuated the Crimea in late 1920 as part of what came to be called Wrangel's Fleet.<ref>Polmar & Noot, pp. 68–69</ref> They ultimately were granted asylum in Bizerte in February 1921. ''AG-22'' was abandoned there in November 1923 and subsequently scrapped.<ref>Polmar & Noot, pp. 68–69, 239–40</ref>
